******
[1] Scotland, June 2013
Date: Fri 28 Jun 2013
Source: Farmers Guardian [summarised, edited]
http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/business/third-case-of-schmallenberg-found-in-aberdeenshire/56828.article


A 3rd case of case of Schmallenberg virus (SBV) has been confirmed in Aberdeenshire, with more cases expected in the area in the near future.

The latest case involved a homebred heifer calf on a farm north of Aberdeen which was found to have deformities typical of SBV and tested positive for the virus.

PCR testing was carried out by Moredun Research Institute following a post-mortem examination of the calf undertaken by SAC Consulting, Veterinary Services.

SAC Veterinary Services Manager Brian Hosie said: "Although we cannot predict what will happen, given that there have now been 3 cases of SBV in Aberdeenshire, it is likely that further cases will be identified in the area in the near future.

Initial investigations suggest the virus was possibly introduced to Aberdeenshire with store cattle brought in from infected areas last autumn [2012]. Midges could have spread the virus from the store cattle to the homebred stock over the late autumn/early winter [2012-2013], according to SAC.

The cases in Aberdeenshire, in northern Scotland, highlight how the disease has spread across virtually all of mainland Britain. Figures published by the Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency (AHVLA) in April 2013 showed how the 1750 cases recorded in Britain had been spread across every county in England and Wales and much of Scotland. But at the time, AHVLA reported that all cases outside of Dumfries and Galloway in 9 other counties related to animals introduced into Scotland from areas where SBV had been reported.

SRUC advises any farmers who encounter foetal abnormalities, stillbirths, or newborns showing signs of nervous disease [to] contact their vet or local SAC Consulting: Veterinary Services Disease Surveillance Centre (DSC). They should not assume these are SBV cases, as other diseases can cause birth defects in lambs and calves, and it is important to know which disease you are dealing with.

[Byline: Alistair Driver]

