[3] Belgium, incidence in sheep
Date: Sun 30 Jun 2013 [accessed]
Source: Emerging Infectious Diseases, Vol. 19 (7), Dispatch, July 2013 [summarized, edited]
http://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid1907.121768


Schmallenberg virus among female lambs, Belgium, 2012. Authors: Claine F, Coupeau D, Wiggers L, Muylkens B, Kirschvink N.

1. Abstract
Reemergence of SBV occurred among lambs (n=50) in a sheep flock in Belgium between mid-July and mid-October 2012. Bimonthly assessment by quantitative reverse transcription PCR and seroneutralization demonstrated that 100 percent of the lambs were infected. Viremia duration may be longer in naturally infected than in experimentally infected animals.

2. Concluding part
The data collected during this study demonstrate that even in regions with a high SBV seroprevalence, viral circulation and primary infection of naive animals occur. In addition to the question of duration of colostral protection, this observation raises questions about virus hosts. It might be hypothesized that other species are reservoirs. In autumn 2011, a seroprevalence of 43 percent was found in deer in the province of Namur, suggesting that deer might have been a reservoir during 2011-2012. Serum samples of 3 roe deer hunted in autumn 2012 in the forest near the sheep flock observed in this study tested positive by SN assay, indicating a higher percentage of seroconversion among samples from deer in 2012. It might further be speculated that notable vector activity favored viral circulation. During the summer 2007 serotype 8 bluetongue virus outbreak, vector activity was assessed among the study flock of sheep and revealed substantial numbers of newly emerged female culicoides spp. midges. This peak activity of vectors paralleled the episode of clinical serotype 8 bluetongue virus manifestation. Hypothesizing that the local culicoides spp. midge population did not substantially change over the years, the intense infection rate during August-September 2012 could be related to increased seasonal vector activity.

Although reemergence of SBV among cattle is of concern, reemergence of SBV among sheep and goats is of particular importance, because high prolificacy and intensive reproduction of sheep and goats continuously lead to a noteworthy percentage of susceptible animals among the population. Moreover, the early onset of puberty in these species increases the probability of SBV infection at an early stage of gestation, leading to potential virus overwintering by transplacental infection of offspring, which could potentially lead to economic loss related to death or culling of offspring. Detailed knowledge about duration of viremia after natural SBV infection and duration of colostral protection are necessary for elaboration of efficient breeding and vaccination strategies.

--
Communicated by:
Faina Golender

[Infections with SBV have so far been reportedly identified in the following European countries: Germany, Netherlands, Belgium, UK and Northern Ireland, France, Italy, Luxembourg, Spain, Denmark, Estonia, Ireland, Norway, Sweden, Finland, Poland, Austria, Switzerland and Serbia. According to indirect reports, Hungary and Slovenia were affected as well, but official confirmation has, so far, not come to our attention. As long as SBV remains a non-notifiable disease, its actual distribution will remain unclear.

The SBV situation in Europe was included in the itinerary of the recent annual session of the OIE. Results of those discussions will be posted when they become available. - Mod.AS

